Package com.github.tommyettinger.cringe

Class Vector5

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.cringe.Vector5
All Implemented Interfaces:
com.badlogic.gdx.math.Vector<Vector5>
public class Vector5 extends Object implements com.badlogic.gdx.math.Vector<Vector5>
A 5D vector, with mutable float fields. Allows chaining operations by returning a reference to itself in all modification methods.

      public boolean isOnLine(Vector5 other, float epsilon)
      Returns true if this vector is on the same line as the other vector when infinite lines are drawn through the origin and the given vectors. Uses the given epsilon to determine if very nearby points should be equal.
      Credit to The yama library for the general algorithm; it is MIT-licensed.
      Specified by:
      isOnLine in interface com.badlogic.gdx.math.Vector<Vector5>
      Parameters:
      other - the other vector to draw a line into from the origin
      epsilon - used as the tolerance when values may be very close to 0 or each other
      Returns:
      true if this vector is in line with the other vector (either in the same or the opposite direction)

    • fract

      public Vector5 fract()
      Sets each component so it only has a fractional value, by subtracting the floor from each component. This produces a non-negative float for each component, between 0.0 inclusive and 1.0 exclusive, unless a component is outside the safe range for MathUtils.floor(float) (-16384.0 at the lowest). 
       The result of fract() for a component with a value of  1.25 will be 0.25 .
 The result of fract() for a component with a value of -1.25 will be 0.75 .
      Returns:
      this, after modifications
